    "system_description": "Hindi ergative-split disambiguation. In the past tense, Hindi is ergative: the transitive subject takes postposition -ne (Ram-ne khaya = Ram-ERG ate), while the object controls verb agreement. In the present tense, Hindi is nominative-accusative. This split means the tense of the sentence determines WHICH argument the verb agrees with — a second-order DCP event where tense first compresses the agreement-space, then agreement compresses the subject-role. Object marking with -ko distinguishes specific/animate objects from bare objects.",
